Three people were yesterday reported to have died of cholera.
 The county health executive, Gichuiya Nthuraku, said those admitted to various hospitals had diarrhoea and vomiting. 
 ALSO READ:

Two infants die as house goes up in flames

 "We have already deployed our officers to the affected areas. We are doing our best to contain the situation," said Nthuraku.
 He added: "I have been leading a team of county health officials to Magutuni, Kamonka, Chuka, Mutino, and other areas where the outbreak has been reported. The situation is under control."




(adsbygoogle = window.adsbygoogle || []).push({});

 He urged residents from the affected areas to observe hygiene. He advised the people to use toilets and latrines and drink boiled water to curb the spread of the disease, which is spread through the consumption of contaminated food. 
 The Kenya Red Cross Society yesterday flagged off a consignment of drugs and 15 health personnel to fight cholera in the county. 
